## Critical Conventions

### Case conversion — a frequent source of bugs

| Location | Convention | Example |
|----------|-----------|---------|
| All Clojure code | kebab-case | `:password-hash`, `:created-at` |
| Database boundary only | snake_case | `password_hash`, `created_at` |
| API/JSON boundary only | camelCase | `passwordHash`, `createdAt` |

Convert **only at boundaries** — never in business logic:

```clojure
;; At persistence boundary — db record → Clojure entity
(defn db->entity [row]
  (clojure.set/rename-keys row {:created_at  :created-at
                                 :updated_at  :updated-at
                                 :user_id     :user-id}))

;; At persistence boundary — Clojure entity → db params
(defn entity->db [entity]
  (clojure.set/rename-keys entity {:created-at  :created_at
                                    :updated-at  :updated_at
                                    :user-id     :user_id}))
```

### Adding new fields — always synchronise all three

1. Malli schema in `schema.clj`
2. Database column (new migration file)
3. Persistence layer transformations in `shell/persistence.clj`

Missing any one of these causes `nil` values or SQL errors at runtime.

### Exception handling — always include `:type`

```clojure
;; ❌ WRONG — no :type causes generic 500 errors
(throw (ex-info "Not found" {:id user-id}))

;; ✅ CORRECT
(throw (ex-info "User not found"
                {:type    :not-found
                 :id      user-id
                 :message "No user with this ID exists"}))
```

Valid `:type` values: `:validation-error` `:not-found` `:unauthorized` `:forbidden` `:conflict` `:internal-error`

### Parenthesis repair

Never manually fix unbalanced parentheses — use the tool:

```bash
clj-paren-repair src/{{project-ns}}/core/product.clj
```

