## Common Pitfalls

### 1. defrecord changes require full restart

`(reset)` does not recreate defrecord instances. After changing a defrecord:

```clojure
(halt)
(go)
```

### 2. snake_case vs kebab-case mixing

Using `(:password_hash user)` instead of `(:password-hash user)` returns `nil`. Always use kebab-case internally; convert only at the DB boundary.

### 3. Core depending on shell

If you see `(:require [{{project-ns}}.shell.*])` inside a `core/` namespace, that is an FC/IS violation. Move the dependency to a port protocol instead.

### 4. Missing `:type` in ex-info

Any `(ex-info ...)` without a `:type` key in ex-data will produce a generic 500 error with no useful message. Always include `:type`.

### 5. Validation in wrong layer

```clojure
;; ❌ WRONG — validation (a side effect decision) in core
(defn create-product [data]
  (when-not (valid? data) (throw ...)))

;; ✅ CORRECT — validate in shell, pass clean data to core
(defn create-product-service [data]
  (let [[valid? errors clean] (validate data)]
    (if valid?
      (product-core/create clean)
      (throw (ex-info "Validation failed" {:type :validation-error :errors errors})))))
```

### 6. Forward references

Clojure compiles top-to-bottom. Private helpers must be defined **above** the functions that call them.

